which plaintiffs will be claiming the most damages, and therefore, to help u=
s=20
decide which method of choosing ten representative plaintiffs would most=20
benefit us.

In doing so, we gave plaintiffs the benefit of the Rhodes Study's=20
methodology, with two exceptions:  (1)  for a given plaintiff, Rhodes added=20
up only the undertaken "values," disregarding entirely and thus failing to=20
offset overtaken "values;" in the scenarios on p. 1 and p. 2, we credited a=20
given plaintiff's overtaken values against that plaintiff's undertaken=20
amount;  (2)  Rhodes also added an "interest" calculation" to his numbers; w=
e=20
did not use his interest calculations at all, because they are totally wrong=
=20
